The write-down of European debt is inevitable
Berkeley — "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the crisis of Greece and Ireland," people used to think, but now it's no longer the case, because it's clearly become a crisis for the eurozone.
To deal with it is both easier and more difficult than usually anticipated.
The economics behind this crisis is quite straightforward.
Greece's finances are in trouble.
Ireland's banking sector is in trouble.
Portugal's private debt market is in trouble.
Spain has problems in all three of the aforementioned areas.
Despite the differences in details, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to go through a painful process of spending cuts.
To offset the side effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic spending cuts with currency depreciation.
Currency depreciation enhances export competitiveness, meaning using external demand to compensate for domestic demand.
However, these countries are all eurozone members and do not have independent currencies to depreciate, so they can only use internal depreciation as a substitute for external depreciation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
In fact, these crisis countries have made considerable efforts to tighten their belts.
However, there is one economic variable that has not changed with the adjustment of other variables, that is, the debt of the public and private sectors.
The book value of government debt has not changed, and bank debt — except for some debt owed to junior creditors — has also remained largely unchanged.
It is precisely this simple fact that has put the internal depreciation strategy into a contradictory situation: the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes relative to wage cuts and other cost reductions.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending needs to be cut and taxes increased to meet the debt of the government and its defenders (such as banks).
This, in turn, demands more internal depreciation, further increasing the debt burden, leading to a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a depression.
Therefore, for the internal depreciation strategy to take effect, it is necessary to find ways to reduce the face value of debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and bank debts should be written off when banks are insolvent.
Mortgage debt must also be written down.
Policy makers are unwilling to take this path, which is understandable.
The contract is sacred.
The government is concerned about losing trust in the financial markets.
If the creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, write-downs would only burden other countries.
These concerns are not entirely unfounded, but one should not draw unreasonable conclusions from them.
The only options are internal depreciation or external depreciation.
The eurozone leaders must choose one of the two options.
They all ruled out the path of external depreciation.
But internal depreciation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is both illogical and unreasonable.
Debt restructuring is straightforward and clear.
The government can issue a batch of debts with face values discounted by a certain proportion from the current debt face value.
Bondholders can choose either to hold onto their bonds and redeem them at face value upon maturity, which will be later in time but with a lower interest rate, or to accept discounted bonds with a face value lower than the current one, which will mature earlier and carry a higher interest rate.
This is not some cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to succeed, there are three prerequisites.
The first is to assure bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone has to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, during the Latin American debt restructuring implemented under the Brady Plan, the U.S. Treasury played the role of the "guarantor big brother."
Nowadays, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, all countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, debt restructuring in one country would raise expectations in other countries, leading to contagion effects.
Finally, banks that suffer losses due to debt restructuring must have their balance sheets strengthened.
These banks need to undergo genuine stress tests, not the token exercises conducted earlier this year.
If debt restructuring signals capital insufficiency, a comprehensive debt-to-equity conversion of the relevant bank assets must be carried out.
If that is not enough, the government must step in to inject capital into the relevant banks.
This provision also requires all countries to act in unison.
Once the banks' balance sheets are stabilized, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debts without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's address the biggest challenge.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that the country's banks have significant risk exposure to debt in peripheral eurozone countries, and the situation is urgent.
They must convince the backroom bosses and voters that guaranteeing debt restructuring and bank recapitalization with public funds is a necessary condition for internal depreciation; since Germany has urged other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should take on the responsibility of guaranteeing it without hesitation.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to portray the consequences more seriously — otherwise, they will face major difficulties.
Because that is the reality.
